Further development started for stainless steel foams based on the alloys 316 L and 321. Stainless steel alloys are introduced and certified for many industrial processes and products, for example in:


food industry;

medical technology;

aerospace application;

automotive engineering;

chemical plant engineering.

An interesting solution for a couple of applications is the combination of compact metal sheet and foam material by a sinter bonding process. Such metal foam sandwich structures with different top layer materials are not only focused on light weight constructions.5,6 The material mix can combine a couple of different properties such as:


light weight;

high stiffness;

low back pressure;

heat transfer;

good damping;

efficient mixing of gases and fluids;

high-catalytic performance.

Depending on loading and geometry, sandwich panels or beams may fail in different modes. The most important failure modes during design and analysis are highlighted as follows:12,14


face yield or fracture;

face wrinkle;

core shear failure;

shear crimping;

local indentation;

interfacial bond failure.
